7 Nov / 910 996 / 2195

It is sometimes difficult to assess until to what point in time the numbers were collected. Over a week, it appears that there were 20 979 new reported cases, averaging about 3000 cases PER DAY. At that rate, it would take about 30 days to reach 1 million cases, although the newly reported cases are decreasing.

In 2015 WHO reported a total of 172 454 cases worldwide in 42 countries (http://apps.who.int/iris/bitstream/10665/250142/1/WER9138.pdf).
In 2016, the total number of cases was 132 121 from 38 countries (http://apps.who.int/iris/bitstream/10665/258910/1/WER9236.pdf).

This continuing, record-breaking cholera disaster in Yemen is only about a bit more than 6 months old and is 6.9 times the total number of global cases of 2016, and 2.68 times the entire peak year of the Haiti outbreak (2011) of 340 311 cases. The low case fatality rate of 0.26 percent might suggest that some of the diarrhea may be non-cholera. There are now as many cases in over 6 months than in the entire 7 years of the Haitian cholera disaster. - Mod.LL

A HealthMap/ProMED-mail map can be accessed at: https://promedmail.org/promed-post?place=5431389,126.]
